{"title_page": "Lend Me Your Comb", "text_new": "{{For|the song with a similar title|Kookie, Kookie (Lend Me Your Comb)}}\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Lendm34.jpg|thumb|A picture of \"Sun 287: The Rockin' Guitar Man\" in 45 format.]]\n\"'''Lend Me Your Comb'''\" is a 1957 song written by [[Kay Twomey]], [[Fred Wise (songwriter)|Fred Wise]], and [[Ben Weisman]]. [[Carl Perkins]] and his brother Jay performed the song for the B-Side of \"[[Glad All Over (Carl Perkins song)|Glad All Over]]\", which was released by Sun Records on the \"Sun 287: The Rockin' Guitar Man\" record.<ref>Perkins, Carl, and David McGee. ''Go, Cat, Go!: The Life and Times of Carl Perkins, The King of Rockabilly''. Hyperion Press, 1996.</ref>\n\n[[The Beatles]] recorded a rendition of the song in [[London]] in 1963 and frequently performed it live. \"Lend Me Your Comb\" has been included on several of The Beatles' compilations and greatest hits albums.\n\nThe song also appears in the 1983 film ''[[The Outsiders (film)|The Outsiders]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Carl Perkins]]\n*[[1957 in music]]\n*[[1963 in music]]\n*[[Rockabilly]]\n*[[Rock'n'Roll]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n*Perkins, Carl, and David McGee. ''Go, Cat, Go!: The Life and Times of Carl Perkins, The King of Rockabilly''. Hyperion Press, 1996. {{ISBN|0-7868-6073-1}}\n*Morrison, Craig. ''Go Cat Go!: Rockabilly Music and Its Makers''. University of Illinois Press, 1998.\n\n[[Category:The Beatles songs]]\n[[Category:Hoodoo Gurus songs]]\n[[Category:Carl Perkins songs]]\n[[Category:1956 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by Ben Weisman]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Kay Twomey]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Fred Wise (songwriter)]]\n[[Category:The Beatles and radio]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the song with a similar title|Kookie, Kookie (Lend Me Your Comb)}}\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Lendm34.jpg|thumb|A picture of \"Sun 287: The Rockin' Guitar Man\" in 45 format.]]\n\"'''Lend Me Your Comb'''\" is a 1957 song written by [[Kay Twomey]], [[Fred Wise (songwriter)|Fred Wise]], and [[Ben Weisman]]. [[Carl Perkins]] and his brother Jay performed the song for the B-Side of \"[[Glad All Over (Carl Perkins song)|Glad All Over]],\" released on Sun Records as \"Sun 287: The Rockin' Guitar Man\".<ref>Perkins, Carl, and David McGee. ''Go, Cat, Go!: The Life and Times of Carl Perkins, The King of Rockabilly''. Hyperion Press, 1996.</ref>\n\n[[The Beatles]] recorded a rendition of the song in [[London]] in 1963 and frequently performed it live. \"Lend Me Your Comb\" has been included on several of The Beatles compilations and greatest hits albums.\n\nThe song also appears in the 1983 film ''[[The Outsiders (film)|The Outsiders]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Carl Perkins]]\n*[[1957 in music]]\n*[[1963 in music]]\n*[[Rockabilly]]\n*[[Rock'n'Roll]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n*Perkins, Carl, and David McGee. ''Go, Cat, Go!: The Life and Times of Carl Perkins, The King of Rockabilly''. Hyperion Press, 1996. {{ISBN|0-7868-6073-1}}\n*Morrison, Craig. ''Go Cat Go!: Rockabilly Music and Its Makers''. University of Illinois Press, 1998.\n\n[[Category:The Beatles songs]]\n[[Category:Hoodoo Gurus songs]]\n[[Category:Carl Perkins songs]]\n[[Category:1956 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by Ben Weisman]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Kay Twomey]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Fred Wise (songwriter)]]\n[[Category:The Beatles and radio]]\n", "name_user": "Pratat", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor grammar edits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lend_Me_Your_Comb"}
{"title_page": "Charlie Snell", "text_new": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Charlie Snell\n|position=[[Catcher]]\n|image=\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1893|11|29}}\n|birth_place=[[Hampstead, Maryland]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1988|4|4|1893|11|29}}\n|death_place=[[Reading, Pennsylvania]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=July 19\n|debutyear={{mlby|1912}}\n|debutteam=[[St. Louis Browns]]\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=August 14\n|finalyear={{mlby|1912}}\n|finalteam=[[St. Louis Browns]]\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.211\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=0\n|stat3label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=0\n|teams=\n*[[St. Louis Browns]] ({{mlby|1912}})\n}}\n'''Charles Anthony Snell''' (born '''Charles Anthony Schnell'''; November 29, 1893 &ndash; April 4, 1988), was a [[Major League Baseball]] [[catcher]] who played in {{mlby|1912}} with the [[St. Louis Browns]]. He batted and threw right-handed.  Snell had a .211 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] in 8 games, 4 hits in 19 at-bats, in his one-year career.\n\nAfter his time, with St. Louis, he played minor league baseball with the Montgomery Rebels and Memphis Chickasaws of the [[Southern Association]] in 1913, the two Toronto teams in 1914 and the [[Chambersburg Maroons]] of the [[Blue Ridge League]] in 1915.\n\nHe was born in [[Hampstead, Maryland]], and died in [[Reading, Pennsylvania]].\n\n==External links==\n{{Baseballstats|br=s/snellch01|brm=snell-001cha}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Snell, Charlie}}\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball catchers]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Maryland]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Browns players]]\n[[Category:Montgomery Rebels players]]\n[[Category:Memphis Chickasaws players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Maple Leafs (International League) players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Beavers players]]\n[[Category:Chambersburg Maroons players]]\n[[Category:People from Hampstead, Maryland]]\n\n\n{{US-baseball-catcher-1890s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Charlie Snell\n|position=[[Catcher]]\n|image=\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1893|11|29}}\n|birth_place=[[Hampstead, Maryland]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1988|4|4|1893|11|29}}\n|death_place=[[Reading, Pennsylvania]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=July 19\n|debutyear={{mlby|1912}}\n|debutteam=[[St. Louis Browns]]\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=August 14\n|finalyear={{mlby|1912}}\n|finalteam=[[St. Louis Browns]]\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.211\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=0\n|stat3label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=0\n|teams=\n*[[St. Louis Browns]] ({{mlby|1912}})\n}}\n'''Charles Anthony Snell''' (born '''Charles Anthony Schnell''' from November 29, 1893 to April 4, 1988), was a [[Major League Baseball]] [[catcher]] who played in {{mlby|1912}} with the [[St. Louis Browns]]. He batted and threw right-handed.  Snell had a .211 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] in 8 games, 4 hits in 19 at-bats, in his one-year career.\n\nAfter his time, with St. Louis, he played minor league baseball with the Montgomery Rebels and Memphis Chickasaws of the [[Southern Association]] in 1913, the two Toronto teams in 1914 and the [[Chambersburg Maroons]] of the [[Blue Ridge League]] in 1915.\n\nHe was born in [[Hampstead, Maryland]] and died in [[Reading, Pennsylvania]].\n\n==External links==\n{{Baseballstats|br=s/snellch01|brm=snell-001cha}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Snell, Charlie}}\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball catchers]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Maryland]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Browns players]]\n[[Category:Montgomery Rebels players]]\n[[Category:Memphis Chickasaws players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Maple Leafs (International League) players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Beavers players]]\n[[Category:Chambersburg Maroons players]]\n[[Category:People from Hampstead, Maryland]]\n\n\n{{US-baseball-catcher-1890s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Deb", "label": "safe", "comment": "punctuation, formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlie_Snell"}
